WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:15.030
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today we're going&nbsp;
to look at lines and parabolas from the point of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.030 --> 00:00:24.570
view of calculus. In a standard treatment of the&nbsp;
subject, where you learn some analytic geometry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.570 --> 00:00:33.690
involving coordinates x and y, we learn about the&nbsp;
idea of expressing a linear relationship by a line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.690 --> 00:00:43.380
in the plane. So, we talk about lines in the form&nbsp;
y equals, say, 3x minus 4, or an alternate way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:49.380
of thinking about that is to rearrange things to&nbsp;
bring everything on one side, say 3x minus y minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:57.150
4 equals 0. And that's not the only kind of line;&nbsp;
we could also have a line that's just y equals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.150 --> 00:01:04.740
something, like y equals 5, or say x equals 14.&nbsp;
These are all examples of lines in the plane in an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:15.510
analytic geometry kind of framework. Going up one&nbsp;
step, we get parabolas, which are second-degree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.510 --> 00:01:26.100
curves in the form y equals, say, 5x squared minus&nbsp;
4x plus 1, or perhaps x equals 3y squared plus 2.

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:36.450
Now, lines and parabolas are very familiar objects&nbsp;
in high school, and students, of course, know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:42.930
lines look like this, and parabolas are some kind&nbsp;
of U-shaped curves that are usually sort of rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.930 --> 00:01:49.620
quickly drawn, sort of like this, and they can&nbsp;
be rather wide or they can be rather narrow like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:57.570
that. The kinds of parabolas that are studied here&nbsp;
are rather of a special form; they're ones that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.570 --> 00:02:05.160
are lined up either up or down. So, a parabola&nbsp;
in the form y equals something like a quadratic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:12.390
expression in x would be something like this,&nbsp;
or something that opens downwards, while this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:18.970
kind of expression usually represents a parabola&nbsp;
that opens either to the right or to the left.

00:02:19.540 --> 00:02:26.260
Now, of course, parabolas are a&nbsp;
special case of a conic section,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:34.240
going back to the ancient Greeks, the idea being&nbsp;
that we take a cone, like this cone here in blue,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:42.460
and we slice that cone with a plane. And depending&nbsp;
on the inclination of the plane to the cone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.460 --> 00:02:47.410
we get different kinds of conic sections. We&nbsp;
could get ellipses or hyperbolas or parabolas,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.410 --> 00:02:54.670
and the parabola is a very special case when the&nbsp;
plane that we're slicing is parallel to one of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.670 --> 00:03:03.880
lines of the cone. That way, we get a one-sided&nbsp;
figure, which is unbounded. If you move it just a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:07.540
little bit like this, you would get an ellipse;&nbsp;
if you move it just a little bit like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:15.880
you would get a hyperbola with two branches. So, a&nbsp;
parabola is a very special kind of conic section,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:20.650
sort of poised between the ellipses and the&nbsp;
hyperbolas, just sort of on a knife edge&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.650 --> 00:03:28.780
between the two categories. From a geometrical&nbsp;
point of view, a parabola appears as a rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:34.180
special object, but from the point of view of&nbsp;
analytic geometry that we're going to be talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:40.660
about today, it's actually a very natural&nbsp;
and fundamental kind of second-degree curve.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:49.870
Now, the usual story that you learn in high&nbsp;
school and in college is that these things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:56.380
should be regarded as functions. So, we should&nbsp;
think of y equals 3x minus 4 as a function of x,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.380 --> 00:04:03.100
or we should think of y equals 5x squared minus 4x&nbsp;
plus 1 as a function of x—in this case, a linear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:11.200
function, and in this case, a quadratic function.&nbsp;
This is unfortunate, and I remind you that you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:16.930
could have a look at Math Foundations 42 A and B,&nbsp;
where I discuss the problems—the very significant&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.930 --> 00:04:23.380
problems—with defining what exactly we're talking&nbsp;
about when we're talking about a function. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:28.120
it doesn't make sense to think that we already&nbsp;
have this idea of a function and then a linear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:33.640
function or a quadratic function is something&nbsp;
contained inside that concept that's already&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:40.030
well defined. So, our approach is going to be&nbsp;
to not think in terms of functions. We're not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:40.030 --> 00:04:44.770
going to take this point of view. We're going&nbsp;
to rather think of lines and parabolas in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.770 --> 00:04:52.180
analytic geometry context as being essentially&nbsp;
poly numbers—poly numbers of degree one and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.180 --> 00:05:00.550
poly numbers of degree two, and that's all. So,&nbsp;
they're not functions; they are just poly numbers.

00:05:00.550 --> 00:05:08.320
So, recall that a poly number, or a&nbsp;
polynomial—pretty well the same thing—is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:17.410
constant precisely when its degree is zero.&nbsp;
It's linear precisely when its degree is one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:25.990
and it's quadratic precisely when its degree&nbsp;
is two. So, a degree-zero poly number is just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.990 --> 00:05:34.870
a single number in the poly number list, and&nbsp;
in standard alpha form, we would just write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.870 --> 00:05:47.650
that as a. A linear polynomial is actually&nbsp;
a degree one—that's sort of degree zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:54.100
degree one—and we would write that in&nbsp;
standard alpha form as a plus b alpha. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.100 --> 00:06:04.000
a quadratic polynomial has a form where&nbsp;
the c here in the second coefficient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:11.080
place is nonzero. In standard alpha form, that&nbsp;
would be a plus b alpha plus c alpha squared.

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:19.870
Now, it may take some little getting used to&nbsp;
the way we're writing this line essentially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.870 --> 00:06:28.750
in this parabola. So, the form here is&nbsp;
a plus b alpha, not b plus a alpha. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.750 --> 00:06:34.840
here the form is a plus b alpha plus c alpha&nbsp;
squared. So, if it was x instead of alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.840 --> 00:06:44.240
we would say a plus bx plus cx squared. It's much&nbsp;
more usual to call the coefficient of x squared a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:51.350
so the usual form for a parabola is ax squared&nbsp;
plus bx plus c. Okay, so we're reversing the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.350 --> 00:06:57.920
coefficients because we have this orientation&nbsp;
that the coefficient-zero term is really where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:06.950
we start, and as we progress down the list, we're&nbsp;
getting higher and higher coefficients, and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.950 --> 00:07:12.290
thing is becoming more and more complicated.&nbsp;
So, for us, the start of the poly number is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.290 --> 00:07:18.350
really here at the constant term, and that's why&nbsp;
our indexing is going in this direction. We'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.350 --> 00:07:25.670
see later on that that's actually quite a useful&nbsp;
terminology, notation, and also later on we may&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:34.730
adjust things a little bit. Instead of using a, b,&nbsp;
and c, we might use a0, a1, a2, and so on instead.

00:07:34.730 --> 00:07:41.480
Now, throughout this discussion, you&nbsp;
have some choice as to whether you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:46.670
want to work over the integers or,&nbsp;
say, over the rational numbers. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:46.670 --> 00:07:51.350
you can think of these numbers a, b, and&nbsp;
c as being integers or rational numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:55.910
and typically, generally, we'll try to&nbsp;
work in the rational number framework,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.910 --> 00:08:01.580
but sometimes integers also. Most of our&nbsp;
examples, the numbers will be integers.

00:08:01.580 --> 00:08:07.910
Alright, so we're going to look at these&nbsp;
three sort of categories here, and naturally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.910 --> 00:08:13.850
the first one is to look at the constant&nbsp;
polynomial. They are just essentially numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:20.030
so the arithmetic of constant poly numbers is&nbsp;
just exactly the same as the usual arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:27.740
of ordinary numbers. And when we represent a&nbsp;
constant poly number in a graph, say this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:38.480
here, the constant poly number 2, well, what&nbsp;
are we doing? We're plotting points where the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:45.650
first coordinate is some number c and the second&nbsp;
coordinate is the poly number evaluated at c. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.650 --> 00:08:56.960
if I evaluate this polynomial, the points that I'm&nbsp;
plotting are going to have y-coordinate two—zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:04.430
two—one, two—two, two—three, two—two—one,&nbsp;
two—two—two. If we had rational points,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.430 --> 00:09:11.450
say in three halves, it'd also be three&nbsp;
halves—two. So, all the plotting points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:17.720
end up being on this horizontal line. So,&nbsp;
a constant poly number gets represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:24.620
pictorially as a horizontal line. It's a line,&nbsp;
but it's a special kind of one—it's a horizontal.

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:33.710
So, when we go up one level to degree-one&nbsp;
polynomials, we have a bigger story. There's more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.710 --> 00:09:42.890
to say; we're talking now about linear polynomial&nbsp;
lines. So, the typical one is something like ab in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.890 --> 00:09:51.170
standard alpha form, a plus b alpha. And to ensure&nbsp;
that the degree really is one, this constant b had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:59.390
better be nonzero. So, for example, 1 2, which in&nbsp;
standard alpha form is 1 plus 2 alpha, that's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.390 --> 00:10:13.820
linear polynomial. But not quite every line, but&nbsp;
most lines are linear polynomials of this kind.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:25.430
This one here—let me remind you how we plot it.&nbsp;
We let alpha be various values, and we calculate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:25.430 --> 00:10:32.030
the value of p for those various values, and then&nbsp;
we plot the value c together with the value p of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.030 --> 00:10:44.030
c. So, when c is zero, then the value is 1, so we&nbsp;
plot 0 1. When c is 1, the value is 3, so we plot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.030 --> 00:10:52.820
a 3. When c is minus 1, the value is minus 1, so&nbsp;
we plot minus 1, and we get a sequence of points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:59.870
like this, moving each time one over, two up,&nbsp;
one over, two up, one over, two up as we move&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.870 --> 00:11:07.430
to the right, and of course to the left, down to&nbsp;
at every step. So, we're getting that line there.

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:16.580
Now, the two coefficients, the one and the&nbsp;
two, have a natural and important geometrical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:24.950
interpretation. What's the meaning of this one?&nbsp;
Well, that's the value that you get when alpha is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:34.340
zero—in other words, it's the coefficient&nbsp;
of y right above the x equals zero point.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:40.970
That's usually called the y-intercept.&nbsp;
So, here the y-intercept is 1 because the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:40.970 --> 00:11:49.460
zeroth coefficient of this poly number is&nbsp;
1. And what is the significance of the 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:58.820
the first coefficient? Well, it's the slope&nbsp;
of the line. And what does that mean? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:58.820 --> 00:12:07.100
if we go over one in the x direction,&nbsp;
then we have to go up two—go over one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:13.880
up two—that means that 2 is the slope. It's how&nbsp;
much you have to go up or perhaps down with every&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:22.640
step of one over to the right. If this slope was&nbsp;
negative, it would mean that if we go over one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:31.370
then we would go down two. So, another way of&nbsp;
saying what that slope is is that it's p of 1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:31.370 --> 00:12:37.010
minus p of 0. If you plug in 1 here, and then&nbsp;
you plug in 0, and you take the difference,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:37.010 --> 00:12:42.860
then these two—this one here—will disappear,&nbsp;
and you'll just get 2. That's an algebraic way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:42.860 --> 00:12:50.360
of saying. So, we have the y-intercept of p is&nbsp;
p of 0, and the slope of p is p 1 minus p of 0.

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:59.960
Okay, and in general, if you have a plus b&nbsp;
alpha, then the y-intercept is this number a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:10.610
and the slope is this number b. So, it's sort of&nbsp;
interesting that originally when we were studying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.610 --> 00:13:18.170
poly numbers, we didn't really think of these&nbsp;
coefficients as having geometrical meaning. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:18.170 --> 00:13:25.430
we see that when we're graphing poly numbers&nbsp;
in this fashion, these numbers do have a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.430 --> 00:13:34.730
natural and useful geometrical interpretation.&nbsp;
That's pleasant for us because we are visually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:34.730 --> 00:13:41.120
oriented and we like to work with lines. Lines&nbsp;
are very important kinds of mathematical objects.

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:49.100
Let me point out that there's two kinds of lines&nbsp;
that we're not getting here. First of all, we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:57.980
not getting horizontal lines. They are not linear&nbsp;
polynomials; lines are special because they're the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:57.980 --> 00:14:05.690
cases where the b is zero—back to that earlier&nbsp;
example of constants. That's a special case;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:05.690 --> 00:14:11.240
that's actually degree zero. And the other kind&nbsp;
of line that we're not getting is a perfectly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.240 --> 00:14:22.040
vertical line like this. That's not represented by&nbsp;
such a poly number because for every value of x,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:27.140
there's only one value of y that we&nbsp;
plot, namely the value of the polynomial.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:40.340
So, a linear polynomial is&nbsp;
non-horizontal and non-vertical,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:47.630
but any non-horizontal or non-vertical line&nbsp;
can be represented as a linear poly number.

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:56.300
So, now that we are representing poly numbers&nbsp;
geometrically, we can apply geometrical concepts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:56.300 --> 00:15:04.040
to poly numbers. And for lines, a very natural&nbsp;
geometrical concept is the idea of parallel lines.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:14.630
What does that look like algebraically? Well,&nbsp;
here's a line p, which is 1 2, or 1 plus 2 alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.630 --> 00:15:23.660
and here's a line q, which is minus 4 2, or minus&nbsp;
4 plus 2 alpha. These lines look parallel, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.660 --> 00:15:30.050
they are. Now we can see that by looking at their&nbsp;
slopes. Actually, it's the slopes that determine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:39.140
parallel lines, because this 2 means that if we go&nbsp;
over one, then we have to go up 2. And this 2 here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:43.910
means that if we go over one, we have to go up 2.&nbsp;
So, the slopes are the same; those lines really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:43.910 --> 00:15:51.860
are parallel. This one has a y-intercept&nbsp;
of 1; this one has a y-intercept of -4.

00:15:51.860 --> 00:16:02.090
Another interesting geometrical notion is&nbsp;
that of the x-intercept—the coordinate on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:02.090 --> 00:16:12.470
the x-axis where the line crosses the x-axis.&nbsp;
Now, for a linear polynomial non-horizontal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:12.470 --> 00:16:19.190
each one of them has to cross the x-axis&nbsp;
somewhere, and to find that x-intercept, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.190 --> 00:16:26.210
we're looking at the x value here so that the&nbsp;
poly number's value at that point is zero. That'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:26.210 --> 00:16:33.080
guarantee that the point that we plot actually is&nbsp;
on the x-axis—it has a y-coordinate of zero. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:39.710
we're really solving p(x) equals zero here. If&nbsp;
we set this equal to zero and solve for alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.710 --> 00:16:46.280
we would get minus one-half, which is&nbsp;
the coordinate there. And if we set this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:52.190
one equal to zero and solve for alpha, we&nbsp;
would get 2, which is this coordinate here.

00:16:52.190 --> 00:17:05.450
Here's another pair of lines, r and s, and they&nbsp;
also look parallel. And r is minus two-thirds,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:05.450 --> 00:17:11.420
minus one-third alpha, which is now a little bit&nbsp;
new because we've got some rational coordinates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:11.420 --> 00:17:20.570
there. But we can rewrite this as a ratio of one&nbsp;
integral poly number divided by another integral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:20.570 --> 00:17:27.350
poly number—in other words, a rational poly&nbsp;
number. So, this is just another way of writing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:27.350 --> 00:17:34.490
this rational poly number. Let me remind you&nbsp;
that we said that the rational poly numbers were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:34.490 --> 00:17:40.340
the second most important field in mathematics&nbsp;
because we can do all the operations within that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:40.340 --> 00:17:49.640
context. So, this kind of object—the same things&nbsp;
apply. It has a y-intercept of minus two-thirds,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:56.510
which would be about there. It has a slope of&nbsp;
minus one-third, so that means if you go over one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:56.510 --> 00:18:04.820
you go down one-third—over one, down&nbsp;
one-third—and its x-intercept here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:11.840
minus 2. If you set this equal to zero and solve&nbsp;
for alpha, you would get minus 2. And here is s,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.840 --> 00:18:18.170
this one here, which is 2 minus one-third&nbsp;
alpha. It's parallel to this one because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.170 --> 00:18:23.870
the slopes are the same—they're both minus&nbsp;
one-third. This one has a y-intercept of 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:31.880
and if you write it this way, you can see that the&nbsp;
x-intercept is going to be 6 out here somewhere.

00:18:31.880 --> 00:18:37.970
So, the idea of parallel lines is very&nbsp;
simple: you just look at the slope,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.970 --> 00:18:45.110
which is the first coefficient. Now let's&nbsp;
think about perpendicular lines, which,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:45.110 --> 00:18:51.470
of course, is the other standard idea in&nbsp;
comparing lines. What does perpendicularity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:51.470 --> 00:18:58.310
look like in terms of the algebra? There are,&nbsp;
in fact, quite a number of different possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:58.310 --> 00:19:04.700
definitions of perpendicularity. We're only&nbsp;
going to talk about the standard one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:04.700 --> 00:19:09.770
but if you are interested in other types&nbsp;
of perpendicularities, some coming from a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.770 --> 00:19:13.850
relativistic geometry, you can have a&nbsp;
look at micro-metric geometry videos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:13.850 --> 00:19:22.250
which are in the WildTrig series from 53 to 57.&nbsp;
There, there's not just a blue perpendicularity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.250 --> 00:19:26.570
which is the usual, but also a red and a&nbsp;
green one. They interact in a remarkable way.

00:19:26.570 --> 00:19:35.180
So, our standard notion of perpendicularity—you'll&nbsp;
agree this is perpendicular to this. And if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.180 --> 00:19:41.030
look at it, this vector here is the vector&nbsp;
2 1 in round brackets to denote a vector.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:41.030 --> 00:19:49.430
Here's the vector minus 1 2, and these&nbsp;
are perpendicular vectors. More generally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:52.580
the rule is that to get a&nbsp;
vector perpendicular to ab,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.580 --> 00:19:58.160
you interchange them and put a minus sign&nbsp;
in front of one of them, say minus ba.

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:07.790
Now, over here, this line has a slope of one-half,&nbsp;
because if we go over one, we go up one-half. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:18.050
this line has a slope of minus 2. The one-half&nbsp;
here is this divided by this, and the minus 2 is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:26.240
this divided by this. So, in general, the slope&nbsp;
here will be b over a, and the slope here will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:26.240 --> 00:20:33.170
be a over minus b. And so the relationship&nbsp;
between those two slopes is that one is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:33.170 --> 00:20:40.550
negative reciprocal of the other. In other words,&nbsp;
the two slopes, b and d, of the two lines—if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:40.550 --> 00:20:48.110
write them as poly numbers—will multiply to&nbsp;
minus 1. Okay, so just make sure you agree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:48.110 --> 00:20:55.160
here. The slope here is one-half, the slope here&nbsp;
is minus 2; you multiply them together, you get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:55.160 --> 00:21:03.890
minus 1. And that's the same as here and here—b&nbsp;
over a times a over minus b—you get minus 1.

00:21:03.890 --> 00:21:13.910
This is coming from geometry, right? If we were&nbsp;
just working with poly numbers, it didn't occur&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.910 --> 00:21:21.320
to us to say, "Oh, it's perhaps interesting if&nbsp;
we have linear polynomials multiply to minus 1."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:26.510
It wasn't clear that that was an interesting&nbsp;
thing to do. But now we see that with this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:26.510 --> 00:21:33.470
representation of poly numbers as lines in the&nbsp;
Cartesian plane, this condition is interesting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:33.470 --> 00:21:38.270
because it corresponds to something that's very&nbsp;
important geometrically—namely, perpendicularity.

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:45.680
There is one more important thing to say about&nbsp;
lines before we leave them, and that's a formula&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:54.020
for the meet of two lines. So, we've talked about&nbsp;
this before when we were talking about geometry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:54.020 --> 00:22:00.890
in the Cartesian setting. We already talked about&nbsp;
lines as geometrical objects, but they were things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:00.890 --> 00:22:08.150
of this form here, and we talked about formulas&nbsp;
for the meet or the intersection of two lines. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:08.150 --> 00:22:16.790
it's a similar story here, but now we're talking&nbsp;
about everything in terms of poly numbers. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.790 --> 00:22:23.840
let's first of all introduce a notion of&nbsp;
incidence. When a point, say xy, lies on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.840 --> 00:22:33.980
a poly number p, we'll say that xy lies on p,&nbsp;
which is a plus b alpha, precisely when y equals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.980 --> 00:22:43.640
a plus bx. In other words, this is exactly the&nbsp;
condition that this be a point that we use to plot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:43.640 --> 00:22:53.930
this poly number. If we replace alpha with x, then&nbsp;
we get p(x) right here. So, this is actually p of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:53.930 --> 00:23:03.440
that, and we'll say that this point lies on the&nbsp;
poly number. That's an algebraic reflection of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:03.440 --> 00:23:09.740
operation of drawing a point and saying that point&nbsp;
lies on the poly number or is part of the graph.

00:23:09.740 --> 00:23:18.710
Now, this particular relation is a linear&nbsp;
relation. It can also be rewritten as bx&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:18.710 --> 00:23:28.460
minus y plus a equals zero. And if you go back&nbsp;
to Math Foundations 24 and have a look at lines,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:28.460 --> 00:23:34.910
you'll see that this kind of linear equation is&nbsp;
represented by the line that we called b 2 minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:42.680
one-half a, with some pointy brackets representing&nbsp;
a Euclidean line. So, whether we're talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:48.620
about this poly number a plus b alpha or we're&nbsp;
thinking geometrically about this line, we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.620 --> 00:23:53.000
talking about two things which are pretty close&nbsp;
to being the same. They're not really the same,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:59.750
but we can certainly, in our minds, compare them&nbsp;
and think of them as being effectively the same.

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:06.770
So, in this video, we stated an important&nbsp;
theorem—the meet of lines theorem—and now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:13.460
I'm just going to restate that theorem in terms&nbsp;
of poly numbers instead of lines. So, if you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:13.460 --> 00:24:20.990
two poly numbers, p1 is a1 plus b1 alpha, and p2&nbsp;
is a2 plus b2 alpha, and they're not parallel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:20.990 --> 00:24:28.900
so in other words, the two slopes b1, b2 are&nbsp;
not equal, then there is exactly one point which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:28.900 --> 00:24:35.710
lies on them both—namely, here it is. Here's&nbsp;
the unique point which lies on both of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:35.710 --> 00:24:47.890
two linear polynomial lines. The x-coordinate&nbsp;
is (a1 - a2) / (b2 - b1). The y-coordinate is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:47.890 --> 00:24:58.690
(a1 b2 - a2 b1) / (b2 - b1). And you can see why&nbsp;
we require the slopes to be different because if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:58.690 --> 00:25:02.470
they weren't different, we'd be having zeros&nbsp;
here in the denominator, which is not good.

00:25:02.470 --> 00:25:08.830
Alright, so I'm gonna leave this to you&nbsp;
as an exercise. Please compare this with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:08.830 --> 00:25:14.170
the formula in Math Foundations 24&nbsp;
for the meet of lines theorem stated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:14.170 --> 00:25:19.060
in terms of lines like that. It's very&nbsp;
instructive to compare these things.

00:25:19.060 --> 00:25:30.370
Alright, so those are really the main things that&nbsp;
high school students learn about lines. Lines are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:30.370 --> 00:25:38.560
pretty simple things for us—they're just poly&nbsp;
numbers with two entries instead of one. It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.560 --> 00:25:47.110
one step up from a number. Now it's time to&nbsp;
go one step more, to go to poly numbers with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:47.110 --> 00:25:57.520
degree 2. Now, that looks like parabolas. Going&nbsp;
from lines to parabolas is a big step up. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.520 --> 00:26:04.210
let's now introduce quadratic polynomials—more&nbsp;
parabolas—and we're going to derive some of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.210 --> 00:26:10.270
main facts about them, which follows and in some&nbsp;
sense is kind of a review of things that we've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:10.270 --> 00:26:17.020
already done in the last few videos. So, I hope&nbsp;
this is more or less familiar to you if you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:22.660
watched those videos before, but perhaps they'll&nbsp;
be a good summary and review of those facts.

00:26:22.660 --> 00:26:30.070
First of all, what is a quadratic polynomial?&nbsp;
It's just a poly number of degree 2 consisting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:30.070 --> 00:26:37.840
of three coefficients, a plus b alpha plus c alpha&nbsp;
squared, and we insist that that third one, the c,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.840 --> 00:26:46.180
be nonzero. And I remind you, once again, this is&nbsp;
a somewhat non-standard form. Okay, in terms of x,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:54.670
this is a plus bx plus cx squared. And we'll make&nbsp;
the same definition that we did for lines: we'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:54.670 --> 00:27:03.250
say that the point xy lies on the poly number&nbsp;
p precisely when if you plug in x for alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:11.980
you get y. So, y is equal to a plus bx plus cx&nbsp;
squared. So, these are just exactly the points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:11.980 --> 00:27:17.380
that we actually plot when we're drawing&nbsp;
a diagram or a graph of the polynomial.

00:27:17.380 --> 00:27:29.320
We talked about the Taylor by poly number and the&nbsp;
sub-derivatives—it's an absolutely fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:29.320 --> 00:27:35.740
kind of thing for calculus. Let's do it here&nbsp;
in this quadratic situation where we can see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:35.740 --> 00:27:43.870
everything explicitly, and it's instructive. So,&nbsp;
what is p of alpha plus beta? That's the Taylor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:43.870 --> 00:27:52.780
by poly number of p—it's what you get when you&nbsp;
replace the alpha with alpha plus beta, going from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:52.780 --> 00:28:00.670
a poly number to a bi-poly number. So, when a plus&nbsp;
b alpha plus beta for c alpha plus beta squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:00.670 --> 00:28:12.190
we expand that out—a plus b alpha plus b beta plus&nbsp;
c alpha squared plus c times 2 alpha beta plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:12.190 --> 00:28:19.150
c beta squared—and then we group those various&nbsp;
terms into the ones that don't involve any betas,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:19.150 --> 00:28:25.240
the ones that just involve a single beta, namely&nbsp;
this one and this one, and the ones involving beta&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:25.240 --> 00:28:32.500
squared, which is only this one here. We see&nbsp;
the original poly number recovered, so this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:32.500 --> 00:28:40.810
what we call the 0th sub-derivative, is just&nbsp;
the original poly number p. This one here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:40.810 --> 00:28:47.050
very interesting and important—this coefficient&nbsp;
of beta is what we call the first sub-derivative,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:47.050 --> 00:28:53.480
or just the derivative of p. Right, so&nbsp;
the derivative of p, by definition, is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:53.480 --> 00:29:03.800
coefficient of beta in the Taylor by poly number,&nbsp;
and there it is there. It's b plus 2c alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:03.800 --> 00:29:15.530
so it's this thing here without an alpha, plus 2c&nbsp;
times alpha. And we also can read off the second&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:15.530 --> 00:29:21.980
sub-derivative, which is the coefficient of beta&nbsp;
squared. In this case, it's just a poly number c,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:21.980 --> 00:29:29.720
the constant polynomial. So, these are the two&nbsp;
sub-derivatives of this quadratic polynomial;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:31.700 --> 00:29:35.420
the other sub-derivatives&nbsp;
are all zero past this point.

00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:45.560
Now, the Taylor by poly number was symmetric in&nbsp;
alpha and beta, so we can interchange the alphas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:53.630
and betas in the previous equation and write&nbsp;
it now as a combination of powers of alpha. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:53.630 --> 00:30:00.620
we're just replacing alphas and betas in&nbsp;
the previous. Well, now what we'll do in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:00.620 --> 00:30:05.180
the next couple of steps is very important,&nbsp;
okay, so make sure you understand what we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:14.030
doing here. The next step is just a rewrite where&nbsp;
we're gonna replace beta, which is a poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:14.030 --> 00:30:21.980
with a number, and let's use the number r.&nbsp;
Previously, for a constant, I was using number c,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:21.980 --> 00:30:26.840
but that's not going to work too well because&nbsp;
there's already a c in our equation, and d is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:30.980
not going to work either because in a little&nbsp;
while we're going to go to cubic polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:30.980 --> 00:30:38.780
ds as well, and their coefficients. So, r is&nbsp;
nice and safe—we're not likely to get up to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:38.780 --> 00:30:46.910
that very soon. So, r is a constant; replace&nbsp;
beta with r—just there's r, there's an r,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:46.910 --> 00:30:52.940
and there's nothing there. Okay, so&nbsp;
this is just another equation—this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:52.940 --> 00:30:59.360
now an equation just involving the poly&nbsp;
number, a simple poly number in alpha.

00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:05.480
And now what we're gonna do is we're going to&nbsp;
replace here alpha with alpha minus r—it's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:05.480 --> 00:31:11.690
translation of this. And we'll replace alpha with&nbsp;
alpha minus r. Well, this becomes just alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:11.690 --> 00:31:17.390
and the alpha here becomes alpha minus r,&nbsp;
and the alpha here becomes alpha minus r,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:17.390 --> 00:31:23.780
and otherwise it's completely unchanged.&nbsp;
So, just this changes, this changes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:23.780 --> 00:31:30.470
and this changes. But this is now a very&nbsp;
important expression—this is the Taylor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:30.470 --> 00:31:37.400
expansion of p at r. So, we're thinking about&nbsp;
r as being a particular value on the line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:44.210
and this is now a formula that tells us how to&nbsp;
evaluate the polynomial at a random point alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:44.210 --> 00:31:53.030
just in terms of the differences between alpha&nbsp;
and r and the various powers of those differences.

00:31:53.030 --> 00:32:01.340
This is a very important formula, this Taylor&nbsp;
expansion, and what it allows us to do, amongst&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:01.340 --> 00:32:11.300
other things, is to read off the various tangents&nbsp;
to a poly number. So, for a quadratic polynomial,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:11.300 --> 00:32:15.080
there's really only one interesting&nbsp;
tangent, which is the first tangent,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:15.080 --> 00:32:22.850
which is what you get when you look at all the&nbsp;
things here of degree 1. So, the first tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:22.850 --> 00:32:34.880
of p at r is this plus this. We're just dropping&nbsp;
the quadratic terms. Now we do some arithmetic;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:34.880 --> 00:32:42.200
we're going to expand this out as a poly number&nbsp;
in alpha. It means we have to multiply this minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:47.420
r here, so there's going to be a minus r times&nbsp;
b here, which is conveniently going to cancel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:47.420 --> 00:32:55.430
with this br here. So, there's still an a, but&nbsp;
what happens to the cr squared? Why does it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:55.430 --> 00:33:02.180
become minus cr squared? Well, it's because here&nbsp;
also there will be a minus 2 cr squared. There's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:10.070
another term multiplying r there, so those minus&nbsp;
two of them will subtract from the one of them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:10.070 --> 00:33:17.570
to give minus 1 cr squared. And then the terms&nbsp;
involving alpha will be just the way they were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:17.570 --> 00:33:35.000
before—b plus 2c r times alpha. What is this?&nbsp;
This is a linear polynomial—coefficients a, b,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:42.650
and c of the poly number, and the particular&nbsp;
value at which we're evaluating the number r.

00:33:42.650 --> 00:33:48.080
So, this is a formula for&nbsp;
the general first tangent,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:48.080 --> 00:33:58.490
or the tangent line, to p at r. It's&nbsp;
a useful and important formula because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:58.490 --> 00:34:05.210
it tells us how to calculate quickly the&nbsp;
tangent line to a parabola at any point.

00:34:05.210 --> 00:34:11.840
So, let's look at an example. Here is&nbsp;
a poly number, a quadratic polynomial,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:19.520
5 minus 4 alpha squared. Okay, so I'm going&nbsp;
to leave it to you to check that the first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:27.140
derivative is minus 3 minus 8 alpha, and the&nbsp;
second sub-derivative is minus 4—this one is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:27.140 --> 00:34:34.820
half of the second derivative, it's minus 4.&nbsp;
Okay, and here's that formula for the tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:34.820 --> 00:34:49.040
line that we wrote down—that's the general&nbsp;
formula for a general quadratic polynomial,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:59.870
get 5 plus 4r squared minus 3 plus 8r all times&nbsp;
alpha. So, this is a linear polynomial—evaluating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:04.850 --> 00:35:11.360
that. So, we can choose different values of&nbsp;
r here, and for every one of those values,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:18.740
we can calculate a tangent line to this&nbsp;
parabola. Here's the actual value of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:26.420
poly number—a graph of the polynomial—a graph. As&nbsp;
I explained last time, we are only going so far,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:26.420 --> 00:35:31.790
and this is a rather crude one. I'm only&nbsp;
looking at more or less half-integral values,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:33.110 --> 00:35:39.470
and actually, the topic appears at minus&nbsp;
3/8—that's when the derivative is zero.

00:35:39.470 --> 00:35:49.850
Okay, so what do various tangent lines look like?&nbsp;
Well, at zero—so, at this point here—we replace&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:49.850 --> 00:36:00.800
r with zero, we get 5 minus 3 alpha. And if we&nbsp;
graph that, that's got a y-intercept of 5 and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:08.090
a slope of minus 3, so it goes down at minus&nbsp;
3, minus 3—there it is right there—that's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:08.090 --> 00:36:17.150
tangent line to p at zero. The tangent line to p&nbsp;
at 1—let me check—there it is right there, it's 9&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:17.150 --> 00:36:28.790
minus 11 alpha—that's the equation of that line.&nbsp;
At minus 1, we get 9 plus 5 alpha. At minus 3/8,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:28.790 --> 00:36:38.090
which is right here, we get 89 over 16. In that&nbsp;
case, the first tangent becomes actually not a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:38.090 --> 00:36:46.670
linear poly number but rather a constant poly&nbsp;
number, so it's a special case. And in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:46.670 --> 00:36:53.810
this is a rather important point on this&nbsp;
parabola, because that horizontal tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:53.810 --> 00:37:01.340
line means that the parabola has a maximum there.&nbsp;
So, the fact that we're not getting a linear poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:01.340 --> 00:37:09.170
number is corresponding to the fact that there's&nbsp;
something rather special about the point minus 3/8&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:09.170 --> 00:37:23.510
for this parabola. And at minus 3, right over&nbsp;
here, the tangent line is 41 plus 21 alpha.

00:37:23.510 --> 00:37:31.850
Now, I want to point something out to you—a&nbsp;
rather interesting little observation. Have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:31.850 --> 00:37:40.040
a look at these two tangent lines—the tangent&nbsp;
line at 1 and at minus 1. These two tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:40.040 --> 00:37:49.220
lines have the property that their y-intercepts&nbsp;
are both 9, which means that they meet right at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:49.220 --> 00:37:57.710
this point here, right on the x-axis, as it turns&nbsp;
out, right on the y-axis, at the point 9. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:57.710 --> 00:38:03.410
that might be a little bit interesting because&nbsp;
the parabola itself is not symmetrical around this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:03.410 --> 00:38:08.390
line—the maximum is actually right there. So, the&nbsp;
thing turns out actually to be symmetrical there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:17.990
as we'll see in the next lecture. But there's&nbsp;
something curious about the fact that we go equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:17.990 --> 00:38:27.890
coordinates away from zero and take the tangents,&nbsp;
we get their meeting at zero. You can check now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:27.890 --> 00:38:35.030
that the y-intercepts of the tangent at r and the&nbsp;
tangent at minus r are always equal, no matter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:35.030 --> 00:38:45.500
what r is like. That's obvious from here because&nbsp;
the y-intercept is this one here, and if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:45.500 --> 00:38:53.030
replace r with minus r, that y-intercept is not&nbsp;
changing. So, it means that if we took the tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:53.030 --> 00:39:01.670
at 3, just somewhere there, and this tangent at&nbsp;
minus 3, that they are going to meet exactly on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:01.670 --> 00:39:11.960
the y-axis. This was a little exercise—you can&nbsp;
see if you can generalize that. What's really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:11.960 --> 00:39:21.650
happening with this phenomenon? Can you state a&nbsp;
more general fact? We'll see how you do next time.

00:39:21.650 --> 00:39:27.770
Next time, we're going to look at this parabola&nbsp;
and problems in general in more detail. There's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:27.770 --> 00:39:33.410
quite a lot of remarkable additional&nbsp;
features that parabolas have—they're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:33.410 --> 00:39:39.200
very fabulous mathematical objects, in&nbsp;
fact. So, I hope you'll join me for that.

00:39:39.200 --> 00:39:42.800
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

